    <item>
      <title>Mercedes-Benz opens its own recycling facility for EV batteries</title>
      <author>
          Jonathan M. Gitlin
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/mercedes-benz-opens-its-own-recycling-facility-for-ev-batteries/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/mercedes-benz-opens-its-own-recycling-facility-for-ev-batteries/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">38b256b0dfafee192826f9a53000550c9bcd0692</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 21 Oct 2024 16:30:22 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;         Making new EV batteries from old EV batteries is a no-brainer.       &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="1000" height="1000" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/24C0345_009-1000x1000.jpg" class="intro-image absolute min-w-full min-h-full h-auto object-cover" alt="A photo of a battery recycling factory—it&amp;#039;s a mass of metal tubes and pipes and reactors." loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/24C0345_009-1000x1000.jpg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/24C0345_009-150x150.jpg 150w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/24C0345_009-500x500.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       This is where Mercedes-Benz reprocesses old batteries into new ones.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Mercedes-Benz                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;p&gt;Today, Mercedes-Benz opened its first battery-recycling plant in Germany. The new plant will use an "integrated mechanical-hydrometallurgical" approach to recycling electric vehicle batteries and expects to recover more than 96 percent of the valuable minerals and metals used in EV batteries.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Mercedes-Benz has set itself the goal of building the most desirable cars in a sustainable way. As a pioneer in automotive engineering, Europe's first integrated mechanical-hydrometallurgical battery recycling factory marks a key milestone toward enhancing raw-materials sustainability," said Ola Källenius, chairman of the board of management Mercedes-Benz Group. "Together with our partners from industry and science, we are sending a strong signal of innovative strength for sustainable electric mobility and value creation in Germany and Europe."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The plant, which is located in Kuppenheim, Germany, shreds the battery modules then uses a mechanical process to separate plastics, copper, aluminum, and iron. The resulting "black mass" is then subjected to a hydrometallurgical process that extracts the cobalt, nickel, and lithium. The plant runs entirely on electricity generated by solar panels and has an annual capacity of 2,756 tons (2,500 tonnes). While this is not especially high, Mercedes says it will use the knowledge it gains to scale up volumes over time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Automakers are increasingly interested in closing the loop on EV batteries, particularly given concerns about ethical sourcing of some of the minerals (like cobalt) and a desire for more resilient regional supply chains versus global chains that have turned out to be highly susceptible to disruption through events like invasions or even a ship getting stuck in a canal.&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;p&gt;And EV batteries turn out to be very recyclable. In fact, &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2021/10/using-recycled-cathodes-makes-better-lithium-batteries-study-finds/"&gt;some data says&lt;/a&gt; recycled battery minerals can perform better than "freshly" refined material.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;That’s Germany—what about here in America?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Here in the US, many automakers have partnered with Redwood Materials, a startup founded by former Tesla CTO JB Straubel. &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2022/02/ford-volvo-and-redwood-materials-start-recycling-ev-batteries/"&gt;Ford, Volvo&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2022/07/volkswagen-partners-with-redwood-materials-to-recycle-ev-batteries/"&gt;Volkswagen&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/09/redwood-materials-signs-deal-to-recycle-bmws-ev-batteries-in-the-us/"&gt;BMW&lt;/a&gt; have all signed partnerships with Redwood to recycle their North American EV batteries, and General Motors recently inked a deal with Redwood &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/05/gm-to-recycle-10k-tons-of-ev-battery-materials-a-year-with-redwood-deal/"&gt;to recycle battery scraps&lt;/a&gt; that are generated during the manufacturing process.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That highlights a problem that battery recycling is currently facing—EV batteries actually last a lot longer than the misinformation put out by EV critics; with active battery temperature management, a pack should only lose a few percentage points regarding its state of charge after 8–10 years.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And before you go to the bother of recycling an EV battery pack because it has degraded below an acceptable state of charge, it makes more sense to &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/science/2023/02/the-big-reuse-25-mwh-of-ex-car-batteries-go-on-the-grid-in-california/"&gt;give it a second life as static storage&lt;/a&gt;. In the whole of 2022, Redwood received fewer than 1,300 EV battery packs. However, &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2023/03/heres-what-redwood-learned-in-its-first-year-of-ev-battery-recycling/"&gt;by that point, it was already profitably recycling&lt;/a&gt; lithium-ion batteries from &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2023/04/vw-and-redwood-want-to-recycle-your-old-laptop-and-cell-phone-batteries/"&gt;consumer electronics like cell phones and laptops&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      <category>battery-recycling</category>
      <category>mercedes-benz</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Solar power from space? Actually, it might happen in a couple of years.</title>
      <author>
          Eric Berger
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/space/2024/10/solar-power-from-space-actually-it-might-happen-in-a-couple-of-years/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/space/2024/10/solar-power-from-space-actually-it-might-happen-in-a-couple-of-years/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">cdf2d258c572391f805f91f8aabc6b0fa0a30aa4</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 21 Oct 2024 16:24:41 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;         From Robinhood to slinging photons.       &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="1000" height="1000" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aetherflux-rendering-1000x1000.png" class="intro-image absolute min-w-full min-h-full h-auto object-cover" alt="" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aetherflux-rendering-1000x1000.png 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aetherflux-rendering-150x150.png 150w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Aetherflux-rendering-500x500.png 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Rendering of an Aetherflux satellite in low-Earth orbit.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Aetherflux                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;p&gt;Like nuclear fusion, the idea of space-based solar power has always seemed like a futuristic technology with an actual deployment into communities ever remaining a couple of decades away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The concept of harvesting solar power continuously from large satellites in space—where there are no nights, no clouds, and no atmosphere to interfere with the collection of photons—is fairly simple. Large solar arrays in geostationary orbit collect solar energy and beam it back to Earth via microwaves a continuous source of clean energy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But implementing this technology is not so simple. In recent years, in search of long-term power solutions and concerned about climate change, the European Space Agency has been studying space-based solar power. &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/science/2022/08/european-space-chief-says-continent-will-lead-in-space-based-solar-power/"&gt;Some initial studies found&lt;/a&gt; that a plan to meet one-third of Europe's energy needs would require massive amounts of infrastructure and cost hundreds of billions of dollars. At best, such a system of very large satellites in geostationary space might come online by the middle of this century.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In short, the plan would require massive up-front costs, with no guarantee that it all would work out in the end.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;A physicist with a plan&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;So when a physicist with a background in financial services told me he wants to reinvent the idea of space-based solar power beginning with a relatively small investment—likely a bit north of $10 million—it's fair to say I was a bit skeptical.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That physicist is Baiju Bhatt, who co-founded the electronic trading platform Robinhood in 2013. Bhatt served as co-CEO of the company until November 2020, when he became chief creative officer. Robinhood has, at times, courted controversy, particularly during the GameStop frenzy in 2021. Bhatt left the company in the spring of this year to focus on his new space solar startup. Space, Bhatt said, has always been his true passion.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The company is called Aetherflux, and it is starting small, with only about 10 employees at present.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It's beyond my creativity how to bootstrap something that's going to be the size of a small city in geostationary space, and I think that's one of the reasons why the idea has died on the vine," he told Ars. "I also think it's one of the reasons why there is skepticism about the idea of space-based solar power. Our approach is very different."&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;p&gt;That approach starts in low-Earth orbit rather than 36,000 km away from the surface of the Earth. Aetherflux plans to begin with a single satellite, launching into an orbit about 500 km above the planet on a SpaceX transporter mission about 12 to 15 months from now.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This initial satellite will be based on a commercially available bus from Apex, which will produce, on average, about 1 kilowatt of power. It's a modest amount, enough electricity to power a dishwasher. This satellite will also include a high-powered infrared laser to transmit this power back to Earth. A mobile ground station, about 10 meters across, will receive the energy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With a single satellite in low-Earth orbit, power beaming will only be available for any location on Earth for a few minutes as the spacecraft passes from horizon to horizon.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"We've spent a lot of time over the last year with folks within Department of Defense, and with some of the folks within DARPA," Bhatt said. "The idea is like do a demonstration mission which kind of establishes the core functionality."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Where is all this headed?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;One of the key aspects of the test is to determine both the safety and efficiency of collecting the solar energy in space, transmitting it through the atmosphere, and then producing a usable source of power on the ground.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If the demo mission works, Aetherflux plans to develop a constellation of satellites in low-Earth orbit that could provide power continuously and at greater amounts. Initially, the company seeks to deliver power in remote locations, such as disaster relief areas, off-the-grid mining operations, or forward operating bases for the military.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"If we can make that business model work, that's kind of the jumping-off point to being able to say, hey, could we put this on things like freight shipping?" Bhatt said. "Could we meaningfully address the ability to do freight shipping across large bodies of water with renewable energy?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Long term, there's the potential to provide a base load of power to augment the intermittent availability of terrestrial wind and solar energy—a key need if the world is to de-carbonize its electricity generation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But that's probably putting the cart before the horse. One of the biggest challenges of space-based solar power is that it has always been theoretical. It should work. But will it work? Trying out a low-cost demonstrator mission in the next couple of years is a fine way of finally putting that question to rest.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Squadron 42’s new 2026 launch date will miss its original target by 11 years</title>
      <author>
          Kyle Orland
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/originally-planned-for-2015-squadron-42s-latest-delay-pushes-it-to-2026/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/10/originally-planned-for-2015-squadron-42s-latest-delay-pushes-it-to-2026/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">d27f74916217c7fa37e62ee3f2c488b014d4aa89</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 21 Oct 2024 15:52:44 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;         RSI said single-player &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt; campaign was "feature complete" a year ago.       &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="1000" height="1000" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Squadron-42-1000x1000-1729525118.jpg" class="intro-image absolute min-w-full min-h-full h-auto object-cover" alt="" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Squadron-42-1000x1000-1729525118.jpg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Squadron-42-150x150-1729525117.jpg 150w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Squadron-42-500x500-1729525117.jpg 500w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Artist's conception of the &lt;em&gt;Squadron 42&lt;/em&gt; dev team flying to a distant star known as "release date."                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Roberts Space Industries                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;p&gt;It's been almost exactly a year now since &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2023/10/star-citizens-squadron-42-campaign-is-feature-complete-after-11-years/"&gt;we reported on the announcement&lt;/a&gt; that &lt;em&gt;Squadron 42&lt;/em&gt;—the single-player campaign portion of the &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/11/star-citizens-6-3-million-haul-breaks-gaming-crowdfunding-record/"&gt;now 12-year-old crowdfunding boondoggle &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;—was "feature complete" and in the "polish phase." Now, many years after &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/11/star-citizen-production-schedule-release/"&gt;the game's original 2015 release target&lt;/a&gt;, developer Roberts Space Industries (RSI) says that, with just a year or two of additional "polish," the game will finally launch sometime in 2026.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The announcement came during this weekend's CitizenCon, per IGN, where RSI founder and CEO Chris Roberts &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1H-0x4xk2Xk"&gt;showed off a roughly hour-long prologue&lt;/a&gt; of the game's promised 30- to 40-hour storyline. IGN also reported that the live on-stage demo suffered "a number of crashes, bugs, and graphical problems," which helps explain why a little more time is needed to get from "feature complete" to "actual release."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-video"&gt;&lt;div class="relative"&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1H-0x4xk2Xk?start=0&amp;amp;wmode=transparent"&gt;https://www.youtube.com/embed/1H-0x4xk2Xk?start=0&amp;amp;wmode=transparent&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/figure&gt; &lt;p&gt;"We did say we were doing it live, risking the demo gods, and they brought their wrath down on us," Roberts said on stage, according to the IGN report. "Both the team and I are confident of giving you this game in 2026. Obviously, you can see it’s not going to be tomorrow because you saw a few crashes there."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The weekend's festivities gave us a bit of a flashback to 2014, when Ars was on hand at that year's PAX East convention for &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5TWQFSzQyeM"&gt;a live demo of &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt;'s "Arena Commander" dogfighting module&lt;/a&gt;. While there, we &lt;a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/IMG_0067-Version-2-1440x960.jpg"&gt;caught a behind-the-scenes glimpse of developers recompiling the game on the fly&lt;/a&gt; to fix a number of live crashes that took place in front of a crowd of hundreds of eager fans.&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="2048" height="1365" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/IMG_0067-Version-2-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2048px) 100vw, 2048px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;                 &lt;em&gt;Arena Commander&lt;/em&gt; was revealed to the public at PAX East in April 2014. From our perch in the press balcony, we could see the dev team on the stage (including Roberts) frantically re-compiling the game so that it would run properly.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                      Credit:                                           Lee Hutchinson                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2014/05/clash-of-the-space-titans-star-citizen-delayed-elite-dangerous-on-track/"&gt;planned May 2014 release&lt;/a&gt; of that module was &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2014/12/star-citizens-arena-commander-dogfighting-hits-1-0-release-milestone/"&gt;eventually delayed until December&lt;/a&gt;. At the time, we noted that "a full release of the Star Citizen MMORPG [would be] expected near the end of 2016," a date that now seems as naive as the &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/11/star-citizen-production-schedule-release/"&gt;original 2015 launch window for &lt;em&gt;Squadron 42&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;“We will build the game you are dreaming about”&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Back in 2014, Roberts Space Industries had raised a mere $67 million from crowdfunders eager to see Roberts' &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/11/star-citizens-chris-roberts-discusses-upping-the-ante-on-pc-gaming/"&gt;lofty vision for a new era of space simulation games&lt;/a&gt;. Now, that funding has &lt;a href="https://robertsspaceindustries.com/funding-goals"&gt;climbed past a staggering $731 million&lt;/a&gt; from players buying &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/01/a-complete-star-citizens-ship-collection-now-costs-48000/"&gt;pricey virtual ships&lt;/a&gt; in a game that still exists only as an unpolished alpha &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2023/03/star-citizen-faces-major-server-outage-still-isnt-close-to-launch/"&gt;plagued&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/06/star-citizen-still-hasnt-launched-but-its-already-banning-cheaters/"&gt;significant gameplay issues&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Roberts &lt;a href="https://robertsspaceindustries.com/comm-link/transmission/19848-Letter-From-The-Chairman"&gt;said in a March update&lt;/a&gt; that the team had "spent significant time looking at what &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt; 1.0 means and what it would take to get there." For now, though, the team "is hard at work, heads down, driving toward the finish line" for &lt;em&gt;Squadron 42&lt;/em&gt;, as highlighted by &lt;a href="https://robertsspaceindustries.com/roadmap/progress-tracker/teams"&gt;the game's public progress tracker&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="1464" height="1101" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap.jpg 1464w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap-300x226.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap-640x481.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap-768x578.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap-980x737.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/rsiroadmap-1440x1083.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1464px) 100vw, 1464px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;                 A fan-designed &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt; development roadmap summary, posted in early 2023.                                   &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                      Credit:                                           &lt;a href="https://robertsspaceindustries.com/community-hub/post/sc-roadmap-advanced-release-view-2023-03-08-OziWec0G5xMk0" target="_blank"&gt;Odysseus1992&lt;/a&gt;                                       &lt;/div&gt;                               &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;The extremely lengthy development path for &lt;em&gt;Star Citizen&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Squadron 42&lt;/em&gt; has &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/07/star-citizen-dev-offers-roadmap-for-development-of-new-development-roadmap/"&gt;become something of a joke&lt;/a&gt; in the 12 years since it first became a crowdfunding darling. But it's not like we weren't warned. In 2012, Roberts Space Industries &lt;a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20121128182541/https://robertsspaceindustries.com/the-pledge"&gt;offered a public pledge&lt;/a&gt; that the use of crowdfunding meant the developer would "focus on quality free of the pressure to deliver by a certain financial quarter." The team also warned that "there may be delays and there may be changes; we recognize that such things are inevitable and would be lying to you if we claimed otherwise."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You’ve done your part, and we will now do our utmost to live up to your expectations," the team wrote in that now 12-year-old pledge. "We will build you the game you are dreaming about."&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The 2025 VW ID Buzz electric bus delivers on the hype</title>
      <author>
          Jonathan M. Gitlin
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/driving-the-2025-vw-id-buzz-was-worth-the-seven-year-wait/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/driving-the-2025-vw-id-buzz-was-worth-the-seven-year-wait/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">73151f2c1330502a345c8cf244b429609e8ae226</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 21 Oct 2024 13:00:20 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;       Here's what it's like to drive—and why the wait was so long.     &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="2560" height="1920" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-scaled.jpg" class="intro-image" alt="An orange and white VW ID. Buzz in a rural village in California" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-1-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       It's been seven years since VW showed the ID. Buzz concept at the New York International Auto Show, but it's now ready for the US market.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Jonathan Gitlin                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="" name="page-1" data-page="1" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/driving-the-2025-vw-id-buzz-was-worth-the-seven-year-wait/" href="https://arstechnica.com/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;aside class="pullbox sidebar fullwidth"&gt;Volkswagen provided flights from Washington, DC, to San Francisco and accommodation so Ars could drive the ID Buzz. Ars does not accept paid editorial content.&lt;/aside&gt; &lt;p&gt;SAN FRANCISCO—In all the years we've been writing about cars, very few vehicles have generated as much attention as the Volkswagen ID Buzz. At a time when SUVs look increasingly threatening, the Buzz seems like an antidote, with gentle curves and something of a friendly grin at the front. Plus, people are starting to get desperate for an electric minivan option, if audience feedback is anything to go by. It's been a long wait for the North American-spec Buzz, but that is almost over, with the first customer cars due in dealerships in November. Read on to discover what we found out driving it around the Bay Area last week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;VW first showed off the Buzz a good seven years ago. It was the fourth time the company tried to reimagine the classic Kombi for the 21st century but the first time that production got the go-ahead. That was in large part thanks to a new flexible electric vehicle platform developed in the wake of &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volkswagen_emissions_scandal"&gt;Dieselgate&lt;/a&gt;. Other more mainstream VW EVs were needed first, however, and it was 2022 before a short-wheelbase version of the Buzz went on sale in Europe as a five-seater family car and also a commercial van.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We drove that one in Denmark, and while it was just as much of an attention-grabber there as it will be here, the short-wheelbase version was too compromised for US tastes. And it was too expensive, despite its smaller battery. European pricing had me pessimistic about the three-row, big battery model, but the rear-wheel drive Buzz Pro S starts at $59,995.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2057350 align-fullwidth"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;img decoding="async" width="2560" height="1920" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-scaled.jpg" class="fullwidth full" alt="A blue and white VW ID Buzz seen by the Golden Gate Bridge on a very cloudy morning." srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-2-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px"&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       Karl the Fog decided to pay his tribute to the ID Buzz the morning we drove it.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Jonathan Gitlin                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;h2&gt;Why the wait?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The main reason for the delay was the wait for VW's revised rear drive unit, which &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/07/the-2024-volkswagen-id-4-pro-gets-a-new-rear-motor-way-more-efficiency/#page-2"&gt;debuted in the 2024 ID.4 crossover&lt;/a&gt;, with a permanent magnet synchronous motor boasting 40 percent more power and 30 percent more torque than the older one and a more efficient inverter. With 282 hp (210 kW) and 413 lb-ft (560 Nm), there's more than enough oomph to stop the 5,968-lb (2,707 kg) Minivan from feeling slow, but don't expect to be pinned to the back of your seat if you floor the throttle.&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="record-pageview" name="page-2" data-page="2" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/driving-the-2025-vw-id-buzz-was-worth-the-seven-year-wait/" href="https://arstechnica.com/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt;Perched in the driver's seat, I'm not sure why you would need to be, anyway. Nothing about the Buzz's driving style demands you rag it through the corners, although the car coped very well on the very twisty sections of our route up the shore of the Tomales Bay.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Like &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/we-drive-the-two-sweet-spots-in-porsches-2025-macan-ev-lineup/"&gt;last week's&lt;/a&gt; Porsche Macan, the single-motor model is the one I'd pick—again, it's the version that's cheaper, lighter, and has a longer range, albeit only just. And this might be the biggest stumbling block for some Buzz fans who were waiting to push the button. With 86 kWh useable (91 kWh gross), the RWD Buzz has an EPA range estimate of 234 miles (377 km). Blame the frontal area, which remains barn door-sized, even if the drag coefficient is a much more svelte 0.29.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="480" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-640x480.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A VW ID Buzz in profile, parked in a rural village in California" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057352" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-4-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The Buzz is 195.4 inches (4,962 mm) long, 78.1 inches (1,985 mm) wide, and 76.2 inches (1,935 mm) tall.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="480" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-640x480.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A VW ID Buzz parked next to a small church in a rural Californian village." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057351" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-5-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       If you have the charge port open, the sliding door will detect it and stop before it hits the charge port door.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Fast-charging should be relatively fast, though, peaking at up to 200 kW and with a 26-minute charge time to go from 10 to 80 percent state of charge. And while VW EVs will gain access to the Tesla supercharger network with an adapter, expect 2025 Buzzes to come with CCS1 ports, not native NACS for now.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I expect most customers to opt for all-wheel drive, but again, American car buyer tastes are what they are. This adds an asynchronous motor to the front axle and boosts combined power to 335 hp (250 kW). VW hasn't given a combined torque figure, but the front motor can generate up to 99 lb-ft (134 Nm) together with the 413 lb-ft from the rear. The curb weight for this version is 6,197 lbs (2,811 kg), and its EPA range is 231 miles (376 km).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's a bit of a step up in price, however, as you need to move up to the Pro S Plus trim if you want power for both axles. This adds more standard equipment to what is already a well-specced base model, but it starts at $67,995 (or $63,495 for the RWD Pro S Plus).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2057354 align-fullwidth"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;img decoding="async" width="1893" height="1893" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6.jpg" class="fullwidth full" alt="A convoy of brightly colored VW ID Buzzes drives down Lombard St in San Francisco." srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6.jpg 1893w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-300x300.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-640x640.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-150x150.jpg 150w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-768x768.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-500x500.jpg 500w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-1000x1000.jpg 1000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-980x980.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-6-1440x1440.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1893px) 100vw, 1893px"&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       I was driving the lead Buzz on the day we drove, but this photo is from the day before, when it wasn't gray and rainy in San Francisco.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Volkswagen                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;While I found the single-motor Buzz to be a more supple car to drive down a curvy road, both powertrain variants have an agility that belies their bulk, particularly at low speed. To begin our day, VW had all the assembled journalists re-create a photo of the vans driving down Lombard St. Despite a very slippery and wet surface that day, the Buzz was a cinch to place on the road and drive slowly.&lt;/p&gt;                                                      &lt;div class="page-anchor-wrapper"&gt;&lt;a class="record-pageview" name="page-3" data-page="3" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/driving-the-2025-vw-id-buzz-was-worth-the-seven-year-wait/" href="https://arstechnica.com/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;h2&gt;A white interior?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;When we got the final pricing and equipment levels for the Buzz &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/08/the-volkswagen-id-buzz-will-start-at-59995/"&gt;back in August&lt;/a&gt;, the biggest surprise to me were the two new interior color themes. Called Moonlight and Copper, both seem like a much more sensible choice for a minivan than the white (Dune) interior of the two Buzzes I drove that day. VW brought some of its ketchup to the event but declined my offer to splash some around one of the white interiors so everyone could see how easy (or not) it would be to clean.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Color aside, there was a lot to like about the interior of this three-row. The view from the driver's seat is commanding, although you sit much further back in the vehicle than some might expect—modern crash regulations demand more than they did in the 1950s, after all. There are cubbies, cupholders, and storage areas throughout the van, and eight USB-C ports, seven of which can supply 45 W. (The eighth is only 15 W and lives next to the rearview mirror, for dash cams.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="1440" height="960" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-1440x960.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A VW ID Buzz interior" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057362" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-9-980x654.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1440px) 100vw, 1440px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       This Copper interior would be my choice for the Buzz.                &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Volkswagen                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="480" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-640x480.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="The VW ID. Buzz main instrument display." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057363" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-10-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The main instrument display is pretty no-frills.                &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="480" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-640x480.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="VW ID buzz with both side doors open, showing the middle row leg room." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057366" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-15-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The middle row is expansive, even with the front seats back as far as they'll go.                &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="225" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-300x225.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="VW ID Buzz third row seen from behind" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057359" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-12-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       At the rear, there are two removable cargo bins.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="225" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-300x225.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="VW ID Buzz third row seen from behind, cargo lid open" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057361" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-11-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       That lid opens for access.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="225" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-300x225.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="VW ID Buzz third row seen from behind, cargo lid closed, third row folded flat" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057358" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-13-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       You can remove the cargo bins and lid and third row, or just fold them all flat.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="225" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-300x225.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="VW ID Buzz interior with the third row and one of the two captains chairs in the middle row folded flat." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057357" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-980x735.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-14-1440x1080.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The middle row is not removable but will lay flat.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Jonathan Gitlin                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="200" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-300x200.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A VW ID Buzz silhouette embossed into a piece of trim." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057364" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-980x654.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-7-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       There are Buzz outlines all over the place.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Volkswagen                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="300" height="200" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-300x200.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="Another ID Buzz silhouette molded into the side of a plastic tray in the center console" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2057365" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-1536x1025.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-980x654.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/2025-VW-ID.-Buzz-8-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Including in some spots you might not think to look.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Volkswagen                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;The middle row offers passengers acres of space, whether via a three-person bench seat or the two captains' chairs that come as standard with all-wheel drive. And you'll find something missing from those Euro-spec two-row Buzzes: windows that open and air vents to heat and cool you.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The third row is the most spacious third row of any SUV or minivan offered in the US, according to VW. Having sat in a few of them, I can believe it—actual adult humans could sit back here and not mind. This row is fully removable, but the middle row isn't. However, you can fold both rows of seats down to create a flat surface, should you need to carry large cargo loads or try camping in it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;VW told us it has more than 230,000 "hand raisers" for the Buzz, but we can expect the allocation for the US to be a fraction of this number. US dealers are apparently being allocated their Buzzes &lt;a href="https://www.autonews.com/retail/id4-success-determine-vw-id-buzz-dealership-allocations"&gt;based in part&lt;/a&gt; on how many ID.4s they've sold. If you want the tax credit, you'll need to lease. The Buzz is built by VW Commercial Vehicles (in Hannover, Germany), a separate division of the company to the bit that builds Golfs and ID.4s, and right now, the chances of adding the Buzz to VW's assembly line in Chattanooga, Tennessee, seems remote.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
